<subSubSection id="C36898C2A673FF9EFF33F9434286F81F" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCDCB49A673FF9EFF33F9434286F81F" blockId="2.[151,1437,1678,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">
<emphasis id="B906175BA673FF9EFF33F943471BF91B" bold="true" box="[199,321,1750,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C72B0CAA673FF9EFD92F94245E6F91B" authority="Morawitz" authorityName="Morawitz" box="[614,956,1750,1775]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrei">
<emphasis id="B906175BA673FF9EFD92F9424575F91B" box="[614,815,1751,1775]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">Podalonia andrei</emphasis>
(Morawitz)
</taxonomicName>
in having a setose propodeal enclosure, appressed silvery setae on the frons and the clypeus, and obliquely longitudinal rugae on the propodeum laterally, but can be distinguished from that species and all other species of the genus by the following combination of characters: male genitalia characteristically shaped (
<figureCitation id="1349D7CCA673FF9EFD19F8D7452AF8AF" box="[749,880,1858,1883]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,1171,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,1165,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Podalonia bicellaris Wang &amp; Ma, sp. nov., male holotype. 7. Head, front view; 8. Head, lateral view; 9. Antennal joints 1 - 5, lateral view; 10. Fore wing; 11. Penis valve and gonostyle, lateral view; 12. Volsella, lateral view. Scale bars (1 mm), 7, 8, 9, 10: 1; 11: 4; 12: 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266687/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">Figs 11–12</figureCitation>
), apical swollen portion of penis valves without spine in lateral view, with five large teeth basoventrally and rounded apically; clypeus flat medialy (
<figureCitation id="1349D7CCA673FF9EFB01F8F34362F88B" box="[1269,1336,1894,1919]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,1171,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,1165,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Podalonia bicellaris Wang &amp; Ma, sp. nov., male holotype. 7. Head, front view; 8. Head, lateral view; 9. Antennal joints 1 - 5, lateral view; 10. Fore wing; 11. Penis valve and gonostyle, lateral view; 12. Volsella, lateral view. Scale bars (1 mm), 7, 8, 9, 10: 1; 11: 4; 12: 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266687/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); vertex, gena (except ventrally), collar, scutum and scutellum with long, dark brown to black setae, rest of thorax with long white setae; forewing with two submarginal cells. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C72B0CAA673FF9EFD1DF8254582F833" authority="Morawitz" authorityName="Morawitz" box="[745,984,1966,1991]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrei">
<emphasis id="B906175BA673FF9EFD1DF82544ADF833" box="[745,759,1968,1991]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B906175BA673FF9EFCF0F83A4516F833" box="[772,844,1967,1991]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">andrei</emphasis>
(Morawitz)
</taxonomicName>
: median part of clypeus slightly convex; thorax with long, black setae; forewing with three submarginal cells (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3B6B8A673FF9EFC6BF8474241F81F" author="Kohl" box="[927,1051,2002,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" refString="Kohl, F. F. (1906) Die Hymenopterengruppe der Sphecinen. III. Monographie der Gattung Ammophila W. Kirby (sens. lat. - Ammophilinae Ashmead). Abteilung A. Die Ammophilinen der palaarktischen Region. Annalen des k. k. Naturhistorischen Hofmuseums, 21, 228 - 382, pls. VII - XIII." type="journal article" year="1906">Kohl 1906</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE3B6B8A673FF9EFBD3F847428AF81F" author="Tsuneki" box="[1063,1232,2002,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" refString="Tsuneki, K. (1971 b) Ergebnisse der zoologischen Forschungen von Dr. Z. Kaszab in der Mongolei. 239. Sphecidae (Hymenoptera). I - II. Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae, 17, 139 - 217." type="journal article" year="1971" yearSuffix="b">Tsuneki 1971b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36898C2A672FF99FF33FF0247C4FEB4" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="448" pageId="3" pageNumber="446" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCDCB49A672FF9FFF33FF024420FE7C" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">
<emphasis id="B906175BA672FF9FFF33FF024703FF44" bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Body length 
<quantity id="4C8A66ACA672FF9FFDCFFF0D44D4FF5B" box="[571,654,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="446" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
. Black, metasomal segment without blue reflection. Metasomal terga I–III, sternum I (except basally) and sterna II–III wholly reddish yellow; mandible yellow in middle and reddish brown at apex; antennal flagellomeres I-VII and tarsi reddish brown to dark brown; wings wholly and tegula posteriorly pale yellow brown, veins yellow brown. Frons except upper area and clypeus with appressed silvery setae; vertex, gena except ventral portion, collar, scutum and scutellum with sparse, long, erect, dark brown to black setae, other portions of gena and thorax ventrally with dense, long, erect and white setae; basal part of petiole with sparse, long and white setae ventrally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDCB49A672FF9FFF33FE014486FD5C" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">
Head. Front view, head width: median length of head = 76: 69. Clypeus width 1.4 × its median length; disk flat, free margin with arcuate median lobe (
<figureCitation id="1349D7CCA672FF9FFD61FE224487FE24" box="[661,733,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,1171,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,1165,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Podalonia bicellaris Wang &amp; Ma, sp. nov., male holotype. 7. Head, front view; 8. Head, lateral view; 9. Antennal joints 1 - 5, lateral view; 10. Fore wing; 11. Penis valve and gonostyle, lateral view; 12. Volsella, lateral view. Scale bars (1 mm), 7, 8, 9, 10: 1; 11: 4; 12: 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266687/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Upper frons coriaceous, weakly shiny, with sparse, fine to midsize punctures 1–3 × diameters apart. Inner orbits of eye convergent at lower part of clypeus (
<figureCitation id="1349D7CCA672FF9FFB25FE49436CFE00" box="[1233,1334,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,1171,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,1165,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Podalonia bicellaris Wang &amp; Ma, sp. nov., male holotype. 7. Head, front view; 8. Head, lateral view; 9. Antennal joints 1 - 5, lateral view; 10. Fore wing; 11. Penis valve and gonostyle, lateral view; 12. Volsella, lateral view. Scale bars (1 mm), 7, 8, 9, 10: 1; 11: 4; 12: 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266687/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
). Ocellar area slightly elevated and coriaceous, weakly shiny, with sparse, fine to midsize punctures 1–3 × diameter apart. ODD: POD: OOD: 
<collectionCode id="ED63538CA672FF9FFE7DFDB14790FDC8" box="[393,458,548,572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">IODP</collectionCode>
: 
<collectionCode id="ED63538CA672FF9FFE14FDB1447EFDC8" box="[480,548,548,572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">IODC</collectionCode>
= 1: 2: 4: 8: 12. Vertex flat and coriaceous, weakly shiny, with several fine to midsize punctures. Gena with shallow, large punctures 1–2 × diameters apart. Flagellomeres IV–XI beneath with long, linear tyloids, tyloids nearly as long as respective article length; relative length of antennal scape: flagellum I: II: III: VIII: IX = 6: 18: 14: 16: 12: 1 (
<figureCitation id="1349D7CCA672FF9FFD7DFD1A4495FD5C" box="[649,719,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1902,1925]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,1171,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,1165,1881]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Podalonia bicellaris Wang &amp; Ma, sp. nov., male holotype. 7. Head, front view; 8. Head, lateral view; 9. Antennal joints 1 - 5, lateral view; 10. Fore wing; 11. Penis valve and gonostyle, lateral view; 12. Volsella, lateral view. Scale bars (1 mm), 7, 8, 9, 10: 1; 11: 4; 12: 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266687/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDCB49A672FF9FFF33FD2047CEFBC0" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">Mesosoma. Collar width: median length of collar = 39: 20. Pronotum coriaceous, weakly shiny, with midsize punctures 2–4× diameters apart dorsally, and with dense, slender, transverse rugae laterally. Scutum coriaceous, weakly shiny, with midsize punctures 2–4 × diameters apart, admedian line conspicuous, extending to 1/3 scutum length, parapsidal lines invisible. Scutellum with several punctures, and with sparse, short, longitudinal rugae posteriorly. Metanotum coarsely coriaceous and dull, with long, transverse carina. Propodeum coarsely coriaceous and dull, propodeal enclosure not delimited by carina, glabrous, with inconspicuous median carina and several inconspicuous, obliquely transverse carina; posterior surface concave medially, and with sparse, large punctures; lateral surface with dense, sturdy, obliquely longitudinal rugae and sparse, fine to midsize punctures. Mesopleuron coarsely coriaceous and dull, with midsize to large punctures 1–3 × diameters apart; episternal sulcus complete and slender. Metapleuron with dense, sturdy, obliquely longitudinal rugae posteriorly. Mesosternum coriaceous, with several fine punctures.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCDCB49A672FF9FFF33FBAA429BFBAC" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1112]" box="[199,1217,1087,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="446">
